How would you design a highly available system on AWS?

To design a highly available system on AWS, I would deploy resources across multiple Availability Zones using Elastic Load Balancing and Auto Scaling to handle instance failures. To handle regional failures, I’d use Route 53 with health checks and failover routing to redirect traffic to a secondary region. This ensures no single point of failure across infrastructure layers.

So elb multi az for health check?

Yes, exactly! Simple way to remember:

ELB Multi-AZ = Traffic routing + Health check based HA

• ELB continuously health checks targets in each AZ
• If a target fails → stops sending traffic to it
• If entire AZ fails → stops sending traffic to that AZ
• Routes only to healthy targets across remaining AZs

ELB Multi-AZ does 3 things:

Function                     Description
---------------------------------------------------------------
1. Health Check              Continuously checks targets in each AZ

2. Traffic Distribution      Distributes incoming requests across
                              targets in multiple AZs

3. Fault Isolation           Stops routing to entire AZ if it fails

------------------------------------------

ASG Multi-AZ = Capacity HA

• Maintains desired instance count across AZs
• Replaces unhealthy/terminated instances
• Rebalances capacity if AZ count changes

ASG has 2 types of Health Checks:

Type                 Default?              How it works
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
EC2 Health Check     ✅ Yes (default)      Checks if instance is running at hypervisor level

ELB Health Check     ❌ No (must enable)   Checks if instance is healthy at application level


Difference:

EC2 Health Check:
Instance running? → Healthy
(doesn't care if app is crashing inside)

ELB Health Check:
HTTP 200 response? → Healthy
(checks actual app is responding)

Multi-AZ in both ASG and ELB together ensures High Availability — ELB stops routing traffic to a failed AZ while ASG automatically replaces the lost instances in healthy AZs. 
This gives zero-downtime fault tolerance without any manual intervention.
